## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Good match if you have soft hands and want a highly aggressive, fast-paced setup for mid-distance rallies.
    - Inner Carbon: Highly recommended. The extra wood dwell time synergizes beautifully with the rubber's dual-gear nature.
    - All-Wood: Excellent match for high spin and control. A crisp 7-ply (like a Clipper) pairs wonderfully with the 52.5° sponge.
    - Mismatch Cases: Avoid ultra-stiff, thick composite blades (e.g., thick Hinoki Carbon), which may make the rubber's non-linear bounciness too unpredictable.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Great for players transitioning from standard tensors who want more safety against backspin without sacrificing top-end power.
    - Backhand: Surprisingly highly recommended. The lighter weight and excellent flicking capabilities make it a phenomenal, spin-heavy backhand weapon.

